---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="About" description="About Citelines — mission and team">
  <h1 style="margin-bottom: 2rem;">About</h1>

  <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
    <ul>
      <li><a href="#mission">Mission</a></li>
      <li><a href="#team">Team</a></li>
    </ul>
  </nav>

  <p>
  Would you trust the information in a nonfiction book if there were no reference to where the information came from? Bibliographies, quotations, and endnotes create trust through transparency, and their standardization holds authors accountable. Citational practices create lines of sight in the complex web of human knowledge, allowing readers to seek knowledge beyond the text in their hands. As Naomi Klein argues,
  </p>

  <div class="about-quote-block" style="position: relative; max-width: 640px; margin: 2.5rem auto 4rem; padding-bottom: 4rem;">
    <blockquote style="font-size: 2.25rem; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.25; color: #1a1a1a; letter-spacing: -0.02em; margin: 0; border: none; padding: 0;">
      &ldquo;Quoting is what we do to bring in the voices of others, to expand the frame, not to narrow it.&rdquo;
    </blockquote>
    <div class="about-citation" style="position: absolute; margin-top: 1rem; bottom: -3rem; right: 0; display: flex; align-items: flex-start;">
      <div style="width: 0; height: 0; border-left: 7px solid transparent; border-right: 7px solid transparent; border-bottom: 11px solid #0497a6; filter: drop-shadow(0 0 4px rgba(4, 151, 166, 0.5)); flex-shrink: 0; margin-top: 10px; margin-right: 10px;" aria-hidden="true"></div>
      <div style="display: flex; gap: 10px; padding: 6px 16px; background: #fafafa; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 3px solid #0497a6;">
        <div style="font-size: 20px; flex-shrink: 0; line-height: 1;">📄</div>
        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 2px;">
          <span style="font-size: 0.95rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1a1a1a;">Doppelganger: A Trip into the Mirror World</span>
          <span style="font-size: 0.8rem; color: #888;">Naomi Klein · 2023</span>
          <span style="font-size: 0.8rem; color: #888;">Farrar, Straus, and Giroux</span>
          <span style="font-size: 0.8rem; color: #888;">pp. 70</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>
  Yet the internet has no such citational practice for image- and sound-based media—the most ubiquitous mediums of information today. In an era where it is getting harder to trust and verify what we see online, we must have public-facing infrastructures that help us determine the credibility of digital images, sounds, and information.
  </p>
  <p>
  Citelines therefore proposes a simple but powerful infrastructural solution: we are building a browser plugin for interactive media citations. Upon downloading Citelines,
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>creators can cite sources within their media, and</li>
    <li>the public can propose, create, and interact with citations.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
  Citelines uses participatory and human-centered methods, like Wikipedia, which will encourage creators and the public to co-create and sustain a robust library of verifiable sources for image, sound, and text in multimodal media. With this infrastructure, we hope Citelines will help disrupt the doomscroll—the passive consumption of content—and encourage public curiosity, knowledge seeking, and knowledge creation. Citelines will help create more accountability, transparency, and interconnection among media makers, while improving internet safety and mass information literacy.
  </p>

  <section style="margin-bottom: 3rem;">
    <h2 id="mission" style="font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Mission</h2>
    <p style="color: #555; line-height: 1.7;">Our mission is to develop this tool and build a non-profit organization. We will:
    <ul>
    <li><b>Build.</b> Oversee the research, development, and testing of the Citelines tool.</li>
    <li><b>Collaborate.</b> Form strategic partnerships with media creators, professional and academic stakeholders, and institutions like public libraries and universities.</li>
    <li><b>Teach.</b> Create and disseminate media literacy curricula for all levels of education.</li>
    </ul>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section style="margin-bottom: 3rem;">
    <h2 id="team" style="font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Team</h2>
    <div style="display: flex; gap: 1.25rem; align-items: flex-start; margin-bottom: 2rem;">
      <div style="width: 100px; height: 100px; border-radius: 50%; background: #e0e0e0; flex-shrink: 0;"></div>
      <div>
        <p style="font-size: 1.15rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1a1a1a; margin-bottom: 0.25rem;">Sowj Kudva</p>
        <p style="color: #555; line-height: 1.7;">Bio placeholder.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div style="display: flex; gap: 1.25rem; align-items: flex-start; margin-bottom: 2rem;">
      <img src="/images/abe-katz.jpg" alt="Abe Katz" style="width: 100px; height: 100px; border-radius: 50%; object-fit: cover; flex-shrink: 0;" />
      <div>
        <p style="font-size: 1.15rem; font-weight: 600; color: #1a1a1a; margin-bottom: 0.25rem;"><a href="https://www.abekatz.com" target="_blank" style="color: #0497a6; text-decoration: none;">Abe Katz</a></p>
        <p style="color: #555; line-height: 1.7;">Abe Katz studies mass communication on the internet. As a tech policy practitioner, he has worked at Meta, mitigating misinformation and building public accountability for social tech; at Discord, where he developed new standards for safety in social tech product development; and at Stripe, where he works on risk standards. He also teaches tech policy topics at the undergraduate and graduate levels. He's fascinated with how big social phenomena like attention, trust, and consensus occur through social graphs on the internet.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .toc {
    position: fixed;
    top: 120px;
    left: max(1rem, calc((100vw - 860px) / 2 - 260px));
    width: 220px;
    max-height: calc(100vh - 160px);
    overflow-y: auto;
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  .toc ul {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
    border-left: 2px solid #eee;
    padding-left: 0.75rem;
  }

  .toc li {
    margin-bottom: 0.35rem;
  }

  .toc li.nested {
    padding-left: 0.75rem;
  }

  .toc a {
    color: #888;
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: color 0.15s;
  }

  .toc a:hover {
    color: #222;
  }

  .toc a.active {
    color: #0497a6;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  @media (max-width: 1440px) {
    .toc {
      display: none;
    }
  }

  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .about-quote-block {
      padding-bottom: 0 !important;
      margin-bottom: 1rem !important;
    }

    .about-quote-block blockquote {
      font-size: 1.5rem !important;
    }

    .about-citation {
      position: relative !important;
      bottom: auto !important;
      right: auto !important;
      margin-top: 1.5rem !important;
    }
  }
</style>

<script>
  const tocLinks = document.querySelectorAll('.toc a');
  if (tocLinks.length > 0) {
    const ids = Array.from(tocLinks).map(a => a.getAttribute('href').slice(1));
    const headings = ids
      .map(id => document.getElementById(id))
      .filter(el => el !== null);

    function updateActiveToc() {
      let current = headings[0];
      for (const h of headings) {
        if (h.getBoundingClientRect().top <= 100) {
          current = h;
        } else {
          break;
        }
      }
      tocLinks.forEach(a => a.classList.remove('active'));
      if (current) {
        const active = document.querySelector(`.toc a[href="#${current.id}"]`);
        if (active) active.classList.add('active');
      }
    }

    window.addEventListener('scroll', updateActiveToc, { passive: true });
    updateActiveToc();
  }
</script>
